00:37:20.500 --> 00:37:22.990
It's not true.

00:37:22.990 --> 00:37:24.295
It's a little bit true.

00:37:26.910 --> 00:37:29.854
The last thing that I'll mention
is cooking with beer as well.

00:37:29.854 --> 00:37:31.520
As you're flipping
through the cookbook,

00:37:31.520 --> 00:37:34.010
you'll see that a lot
of the recipes in there

00:37:34.010 --> 00:37:36.560
use beer as an ingredient.

00:37:36.560 --> 00:37:39.100
Not only is beer fun to pair
with, beer is fun to cook with.

00:37:39.100 --> 00:37:43.280
And adding a beer to a dish is
like adding a spice cabinet.

00:37:43.280 --> 00:37:45.929
Because once you degas the
beer, once you heat it up,

00:37:45.929 --> 00:37:47.470
once you've added
garlic to anything,

00:37:47.470 --> 00:37:50.297
it's not going to taste the
way that it does in our glass.

00:37:50.297 --> 00:37:51.880
It's going to taste
totally different.

00:37:51.880 --> 00:37:56.020
And so you're going to get
deeper flavors from it.

00:37:56.020 --> 00:37:57.660
It could be like using a stock.

00:37:57.660 --> 00:37:59.260
Beer is great in
salad dressings.

00:37:59.260 --> 00:38:00.470
Its great as a marinade.

00:38:00.470 --> 00:38:05.790
Not only does it add some
tenderness to the meat,

00:38:05.790 --> 00:38:08.330
or to your protein, by having
the carbonation nibble away

00:38:08.330 --> 00:38:10.090
at it a little bit,
but it also can

00:38:10.090 --> 00:38:12.480
add some additional
sweetness that can bring out

00:38:12.480 --> 00:38:15.950
some of the more
savory flavors as well.

00:38:15.950 --> 00:38:18.760
Don't just cook with beer for
the sake of cooking with beer.

00:38:18.760 --> 00:38:20.450
As I was researching
this book, there's

00:38:20.450 --> 00:38:23.230
been a lot of your
cookbooks in the past,

00:38:23.230 --> 00:38:25.600
and one thing that
I wanted to avoid

00:38:25.600 --> 00:38:29.700
was people say, well,
add a tablespoon of lager

00:38:29.700 --> 00:38:30.530
and then move on.

00:38:30.530 --> 00:38:33.970
That does nothing
to the overall--

00:38:33.970 --> 00:38:36.620
if you're going to cook
with beer, cook with beer.

00:38:36.620 --> 00:38:39.570
One of the recipes in there
uses an entire six pack

00:38:39.570 --> 00:38:40.970
of a scotch ale in there.

00:38:40.970 --> 00:38:42.630
Which I know, people
are like, well,

00:38:42.630 --> 00:38:44.252
why would you use
an entire six pack?

00:38:44.252 --> 00:38:46.460
Because it's good when it
comes out on the other end.

00:38:46.460 --> 00:38:47.610
And that's why.

00:38:47.610 --> 00:38:50.260
Because anything less than
six or anything more than six

00:38:50.260 --> 00:38:52.730
just wouldn't have done.

00:38:52.730 --> 00:38:55.110
So cooking with beer
can be a lot of fun,

00:38:55.110 --> 00:38:59.180
but not if you're just going to
do it for the sake of doing it.

