AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE].

00:47:28.600 --> 00:47:29.770
JOHN HOLL: Yes.

00:47:29.770 --> 00:47:31.804
Yes sir.

00:47:31.804 --> 00:47:32.720
First times the charm.

00:47:32.720 --> 00:47:34.906
I like that.

00:47:34.906 --> 00:47:36.030
AUDIENCE: I am mic enabled.

00:47:36.030 --> 00:47:37.940
Yes.

00:47:37.940 --> 00:47:40.000
So you were mentioning
the pairing with a steak.

00:47:40.000 --> 00:47:41.666
You mentioned you
have some blue cheese,

00:47:41.666 --> 00:47:43.910
you add either a Porter
or perhaps a stout.

00:47:43.910 --> 00:47:46.882
What is the modern
difference between those?

00:47:46.882 --> 00:47:48.960
JOHN HOLL: God, I
hate that question.

00:47:48.960 --> 00:47:50.490
AUDIENCE: I know.

00:47:50.490 --> 00:47:51.540
JOHN HOLL: Very little.

00:47:51.540 --> 00:47:52.360
AUDIENCE: That's what I thought.

00:47:52.360 --> 00:47:52.810
JOHN HOLL: Very little.

00:47:52.810 --> 00:47:54.726
AUDIENCE: I was always
just kind of assuming--

00:47:54.726 --> 00:47:55.720
JOHN HOLL: Yeah.

00:47:55.720 --> 00:47:57.060
It's evolved over time.

00:47:57.060 --> 00:48:02.161
When you look at the overall
definitions when judging

00:48:02.161 --> 00:48:02.660
is done.

00:48:02.660 --> 00:48:05.777
It can be tough to tell the
difference between the two.

00:48:05.777 --> 00:48:07.610
AUDIENCE: There's even
different categories.

00:48:07.610 --> 00:48:08.401
JOHN HOLL: Exactly.

00:48:08.401 --> 00:48:09.520
It's different categories.

00:48:09.520 --> 00:48:14.490
I Some people make the argument
that it's Irish versus United

00:48:14.490 --> 00:48:16.240
Kingdom kind of difference.

00:48:16.240 --> 00:48:20.700
Guinness versus London
Porter kind of thing.

00:48:20.700 --> 00:48:21.200
Yeah.

00:48:21.200 --> 00:48:24.290
There's not-- there's not a
heck of a lot of difference,

00:48:24.290 --> 00:48:27.080
on its face, of them.

00:48:27.080 --> 00:48:29.820
When you start getting into
some of the larger, or the more

00:48:29.820 --> 00:48:33.390
boozy, complex,
stouts and porters,

00:48:33.390 --> 00:48:34.890
the differences
become more vast.

00:48:34.890 --> 00:48:38.390
The difference between a foreign
Extra Stout and a Baltic Porter

00:48:38.390 --> 00:48:40.960
are a little bit different.

00:48:40.960 --> 00:48:44.510
Yeah I hate that question,
because I get it all the time.

00:48:44.510 --> 00:48:47.240
And I've never come up
with a really good answer

00:48:47.240 --> 00:48:50.700
that people walk away
feeling, you're a genius!

00:48:50.700 --> 00:48:51.890
So, Yeah.

00:48:51.890 --> 00:48:55.480
AUDIENCE: So, much easier
personal preference question.

00:48:55.480 --> 00:48:58.510
Obviously you get asked every
day, what's your favorite beer?

00:48:58.510 --> 00:49:01.000
But within your
favorite style-- if you

00:49:01.000 --> 00:49:06.520
have one-- what is your favorite
beer that you've ever tasted?

00:49:06.520 --> 00:49:09.980
JOHN HOLL: Favorite beer
that I've ever tasted.

00:49:09.980 --> 00:49:10.480
Shit.

00:49:10.480 --> 00:49:11.480
That's a tough question.

00:49:11.480 --> 00:49:12.855
AUDIENCE: Assuming
you don't have

00:49:12.855 --> 00:49:14.360
a favorite that
you've never tasted.

00:49:14.360 --> 00:49:15.862
JOHN HOLL: Right.

00:49:15.862 --> 00:49:16.820
There are known knowns.

00:49:16.820 --> 00:49:19.945
And there are known unknowns,
and unknown unknowns.

00:49:24.190 --> 00:49:27.690
I tend toward stouts
and porters myself.

00:49:27.690 --> 00:49:31.930
It's really sort of my
go to style if I'm out.

00:49:31.930 --> 00:49:33.900
But it really depends
on where I'm at,

00:49:33.900 --> 00:49:39.370
who I'm with, what's
local, what tastes good.

00:49:39.370 --> 00:49:42.320
For the purposes of when I
do beer tastings at home,

00:49:42.320 --> 00:49:45.880
and judging, I keep Sam
Adams Foster and a Lager,

00:49:45.880 --> 00:49:49.230
and Sierra Nevada
Pale Ale in my fridge.

00:49:49.230 --> 00:49:51.420
And that's because I know
exactly how those beers

00:49:51.420 --> 00:49:53.330
taste like.

00:49:53.330 --> 00:49:55.951
They're not my go to's, but
I'm very familiar with them,

00:49:55.951 --> 00:49:57.700
and that helps when
I'm tasting new beers.

00:49:57.700 --> 00:49:59.825
Because if I feel like I'm
tasting something that's

00:49:59.825 --> 00:50:01.740
an off flavor, or I'm
feeling like I'm just

00:50:01.740 --> 00:50:04.260
having a bad tasting day,
I can open up one of those.

00:50:04.260 --> 00:50:06.980
And if it tastes how I know
it's supposed to taste,

00:50:06.980 --> 00:50:08.465
then I know that there's
something wrong with this beer

00:50:08.465 --> 00:50:09.240
that I'm tasting.

00:50:09.240 --> 00:50:10.460
If those beers don't
taste right to me,

00:50:10.460 --> 00:50:12.400
it means that I had
something weird for lunch.

00:50:12.400 --> 00:50:15.180
And it's throwing
me off a little bit.

00:50:15.180 --> 00:50:17.520
There's a couple of beers
throughout the country,

00:50:17.520 --> 00:50:20.510
and I hate playing favorites,
because I run this beer

00:50:20.510 --> 00:50:24.059
magazine where we're
impartial, but there's

00:50:24.059 --> 00:50:25.850
a couple of beers that
I do try to seek out

00:50:25.850 --> 00:50:27.190
whenever I'm traveling.

00:50:27.190 --> 00:50:28.780
New Glarus out in
Wisconsin makes

00:50:28.780 --> 00:50:31.695
a beer called Raspberry Tart
which is just phenomenal.

00:50:31.695 --> 00:50:35.810
It's about 4% alcohol, made
with fresh raspberries.

00:50:35.810 --> 00:50:37.780
It's like a brown
ale with raspberries.

00:50:37.780 --> 00:50:40.160
It's just delightful.

00:50:40.160 --> 00:50:42.720
The Cambridge Brewing
Company out in Massachusetts

00:50:42.720 --> 00:50:44.900
does a Summer
Barleywine that they

00:50:44.900 --> 00:50:49.330
call arquebus that's
about 14% alcohol, that's

00:50:49.330 --> 00:50:51.679
got these really wonderful
boozy vanilla flavors.

00:50:51.679 --> 00:50:53.220
And they only put
it out once a year.

00:50:53.220 --> 00:50:56.600
And it seems like I'm on a
train from New York up to Boston

00:50:56.600 --> 00:51:00.190
every summer just to taste
this particular beer.

00:51:00.190 --> 00:51:01.850
But for me these
days, there are so

00:51:01.850 --> 00:51:03.890
many cool beers to
be tasted out there,

00:51:03.890 --> 00:51:06.296
that I haven't found
my next favorite yet.

00:51:06.296 --> 00:51:07.920
And I haven't found
the next one that's

00:51:07.920 --> 00:51:11.400
going to stop me dead in my
tracks and make me say, wow.

00:51:11.400 --> 00:51:13.600
And that's kind
of a cool thing is

00:51:13.600 --> 00:51:16.240
it just shows how much
the brewers are pushing

00:51:16.240 --> 00:51:18.860
the envelope these days, and
really continually trying

00:51:18.860 --> 00:51:21.639
to make themselves better.

00:51:21.639 --> 00:51:23.180
It's always a lot
of fun when I smell

00:51:23.180 --> 00:51:25.500
a beer for the first time,
like I did with this one.

00:51:25.500 --> 00:51:28.291
And I get this big
smile on my face,

00:51:28.291 --> 00:51:29.790
because I know as
soon as I smell it

00:51:29.790 --> 00:51:31.960
that I'm really going
to enjoy this beer.

00:51:31.960 --> 00:51:34.640
And that's a cool thing because
that still happens quite a bit.

00:51:34.640 --> 00:51:36.867
And you'd think with 3,000
breweries in the country

00:51:36.867 --> 00:51:38.450
that it wouldn't
happen quite so much.

00:51:38.450 --> 00:51:39.708
But it is.

00:51:44.650 --> 00:51:47.530
I'm really digging the cherries
off of this by the way.

00:51:47.530 --> 00:51:49.470
AUDIENCE: So you
mentioned beef hearts.

00:51:49.470 --> 00:51:50.095
JOHN HOLL: Yes.

00:51:50.095 --> 00:51:52.450
AUDIENCE: So ignoring that.

00:51:52.450 --> 00:51:55.770
What's your favorite gimmick
ingredient and your least

00:51:55.770 --> 00:51:58.580
favorite gimmick ingredient
that you've tried thus far.

00:51:58.580 --> 00:52:01.150
JOHN HOLL: Beef hearts
is my least favorite.

00:52:01.150 --> 00:52:02.490
AUDIENCE: Besides beef hearts.

00:52:02.490 --> 00:52:03.781
JOHN HOLL: Besides beef hearts.

00:52:07.510 --> 00:52:10.380
Probably my favorite is coffee.

00:52:10.380 --> 00:52:13.130
I think coffee just
brings so much to stouts.

00:52:13.130 --> 00:52:15.520
And there's brewers that
are trying different things

00:52:15.520 --> 00:52:16.620
these days with coffee.

00:52:16.620 --> 00:52:18.620
We have a brewery
in New Jersey called

00:52:18.620 --> 00:52:22.057
Carton which did a
coffee light and sweet.

00:52:22.057 --> 00:52:23.640
So that's sort of
an East Coast thing.

00:52:23.640 --> 00:52:25.681
I don't know if it's out
here, but it's basically

00:52:25.681 --> 00:52:28.110
like three sugars and
milk in your coffee.

00:52:28.110 --> 00:52:30.890
And so it's like coffee
for kids, essentially.

00:52:30.890 --> 00:52:33.030
And they did a
beer that was maybe

00:52:33.030 --> 00:52:35.010
about this color, thereabouts.

00:52:35.010 --> 00:52:36.770
But it had a good
ton of coffee in it.

00:52:36.770 --> 00:52:38.270
And when you think
of a coffee beer,

00:52:38.270 --> 00:52:40.850
you're not necessarily thinking
of a light colored beer

00:52:40.850 --> 00:52:42.050
as well.

00:52:42.050 --> 00:52:44.630
And so I really dig
that, because they

00:52:44.630 --> 00:52:46.890
use some lactose sugar,
which is milk sugar,

00:52:46.890 --> 00:52:50.040
and the coffee in
it, so it actually

00:52:50.040 --> 00:52:55.240
tasted like a coffee light and
sweet, which was kind of fun.

00:52:55.240 --> 00:52:57.330
Coffee's also great with IPAs.

00:52:57.330 --> 00:52:59.020
Stone Brewing Company
a couple years ago

00:52:59.020 --> 00:53:02.130
did a collaboration--
Dayman Coffee,

00:53:02.130 --> 00:53:04.850
where it was these
bright floral hoppy

00:53:04.850 --> 00:53:07.240
notes with this really
nice kick of coffee.

00:53:07.240 --> 00:53:09.540
And again, lighter color.

00:53:09.540 --> 00:53:12.130
My magazine did a collaboration
with Sierra Nevada Brewing

00:53:12.130 --> 00:53:13.690
a couple months
ago, where we also

00:53:13.690 --> 00:53:16.700
did a coffee IPA with
Counterculture Coffee, which

00:53:16.700 --> 00:53:19.020
is a growing chain
and growing business.

00:53:19.020 --> 00:53:22.240
And we tried different
coffee varieties

00:53:22.240 --> 00:53:25.870
where we wanted ones that had
berry and lemon notes to it.

00:53:25.870 --> 00:53:28.330
Then we found hops to match,
so that it brought out

00:53:28.330 --> 00:53:29.530
those additional flavors.

00:53:29.530 --> 00:53:31.113
So I'm really digging
what's happening

00:53:31.113 --> 00:53:32.812
with coffee these days.

00:53:32.812 --> 00:53:34.270
As I've been rambling
on that, I've

00:53:34.270 --> 00:53:36.360
been really trying to think
about some of the bad stuff

00:53:36.360 --> 00:53:36.943
that I've had.

00:53:39.500 --> 00:53:41.150
There's a lot of
brewers that are

00:53:41.150 --> 00:53:46.070
using rare and exotic
fruits these days.

00:53:46.070 --> 00:53:48.680
And sometimes it works,
and sometimes it doesn't.

00:53:48.680 --> 00:53:51.640
The thing that I'm hesitant to
say about things that I overly

00:53:51.640 --> 00:53:55.620
don't like is that I might
not like it, but you might.

00:53:55.620 --> 00:53:59.639
And then who am I to say
that this is not a good beer?

00:53:59.639 --> 00:54:01.930
And who are any of us to say
that it's not a good beer?

00:54:01.930 --> 00:54:04.010
If somebody likes
the taste of it,

00:54:04.010 --> 00:54:05.580
that's a personal preference.

00:54:05.580 --> 00:54:08.365
I'm sure as we did this
tasting today that you noticed

00:54:08.365 --> 00:54:09.740
that some of you
really liked it.

00:54:09.740 --> 00:54:11.580
Maybe your neighbor sitting
next to you is like, oh

00:54:11.580 --> 00:54:12.420
that's not for me.

00:54:12.420 --> 00:54:14.750
I saw people passing
off their glasses.

00:54:14.750 --> 00:54:17.350
And there's no shame in that.

00:54:17.350 --> 00:54:21.570
Beer is a very
personal experience.

00:54:21.570 --> 00:54:25.010
Brewers are trying
weird stuff these days.

00:54:25.010 --> 00:54:27.010
But it's from the weird
stuff that you sometimes

00:54:27.010 --> 00:54:28.100
get the best stuff.

00:54:28.100 --> 00:54:30.650
And it's that continually
pushing of the innovation.

00:54:30.650 --> 00:54:36.890
It's that continually pushing
of brewers going and finding

00:54:36.890 --> 00:54:38.670
weird ingredients.

00:54:38.670 --> 00:54:41.830
Oyster stouts have been
around for a really long time.

00:54:41.830 --> 00:54:44.650
And oysters and stouts are
a wonderful beer and food

00:54:44.650 --> 00:54:45.150
pairing.

00:54:45.150 --> 00:54:47.970
And so putting oysters
into your stout

00:54:47.970 --> 00:54:49.890
really brings out the
sort of like savoriness

00:54:49.890 --> 00:54:51.830
in the beer along with
some of that sweetness,

00:54:51.830 --> 00:54:54.120
and adds a little bit
of body and depth to it.

00:54:54.120 --> 00:54:55.230
I love oyster stouts.

00:54:55.230 --> 00:54:56.930
But if there's
people here who are

00:54:56.930 --> 00:54:59.750
squeamish at the
idea of oysters,

00:54:59.750 --> 00:55:04.800
or eating raw shellfish,
you're not going to like that.

00:55:04.800 --> 00:55:06.460
And so it's tough
to say ingredients

00:55:06.460 --> 00:55:07.670
that I don't personally like.

00:55:07.670 --> 00:55:09.670
There's some people who
are tea drinkers and not

00:55:09.670 --> 00:55:11.294
coffee drinkers who
are just turned off

00:55:11.294 --> 00:55:13.240
by my whole little
spiel on coffee.

00:55:13.240 --> 00:55:16.160
So it's a tough thing to
really say these days.

00:55:16.160 --> 00:55:19.470
It's judge each beer yourself.

00:55:19.470 --> 00:55:22.537
And if you like it,
drink more of it.

00:55:22.537 --> 00:55:24.370
If you don't, you're
going to find something

00:55:24.370 --> 00:55:25.813
that you will like.

00:55:29.600 --> 00:55:31.904
Questions?

00:55:31.904 --> 00:55:34.260
You guys can duke it out there.

00:55:34.260 --> 00:55:39.490
Is there any of
more this Almanac?

00:55:39.490 --> 00:55:40.640
Somewhere?

