Sorry, I just need to reload.

00:55:46.415 --> 00:55:47.040
I'm not joking.

00:55:47.040 --> 00:55:51.130
I got off of a plane like three
hours ago from New Zealand.

00:55:51.130 --> 00:55:52.982
I've been up for like 24 hours.

00:55:52.982 --> 00:55:54.940
And I still have to fly
back to Jersey tonight.

00:55:54.940 --> 00:56:00.170
So this is-- my seat mate is
going to hate me on the plane.

00:56:00.170 --> 00:56:01.546
Yes.

00:56:01.546 --> 00:56:02.920
AUDIENCE: Yeah
I'd love to hear--

00:56:02.920 --> 00:56:04.086
kind of a two-part question.

00:56:04.086 --> 00:56:07.620
First question is how your
opinion of California breweries

00:56:07.620 --> 00:56:10.100
versus breweries
from other states.

00:56:10.100 --> 00:56:11.750
And then part two
are what are three

00:56:11.750 --> 00:56:13.600
beers we have to
try before we die?

00:56:16.420 --> 00:56:18.696
JOHN HOLL: Good questions.

00:56:18.696 --> 00:56:20.070
California has
the most breweries

00:56:20.070 --> 00:56:22.280
out of any state in
the Union right now.

00:56:22.280 --> 00:56:25.630
So by nature of that, you have
a really big, diverse beer

00:56:25.630 --> 00:56:27.860
culture.

00:56:27.860 --> 00:56:32.370
San Diego is a hop
capital right now.

00:56:32.370 --> 00:56:34.750
They're doing these
really big, dank,

00:56:34.750 --> 00:56:37.542
super hoppy, super
aggressive beers.

00:56:37.542 --> 00:56:40.000
And you're seeing some of those
in other parts of the state

00:56:40.000 --> 00:56:41.300
as well.

00:56:41.300 --> 00:56:44.250
Hops come into big
play in California.

00:56:44.250 --> 00:56:46.920
Whereas other states use them,
but maybe not in the same way

00:56:46.920 --> 00:56:48.280
that California does.

00:56:48.280 --> 00:56:51.740
If you say to somebody a San
Diego, or a West Coast style

00:56:51.740 --> 00:56:54.110
IPA, chances are
that they're thinking

00:56:54.110 --> 00:56:56.780
of California,
specifically San Diego.

00:56:56.780 --> 00:57:00.330
But then you go up to
Berkeley and San Francisco

00:57:00.330 --> 00:57:02.460
and that general area,
where this beer comes from,

00:57:02.460 --> 00:57:04.793
and they're doing a lot of
barrel aging, because they're

00:57:04.793 --> 00:57:06.610
in wine country, or
close to wine country.

00:57:06.610 --> 00:57:07.720
And there's access to barrels.

00:57:07.720 --> 00:57:09.678
And they're really
interested in those flavors.

00:57:09.678 --> 00:57:11.080
And they're
interested in using--

00:57:11.080 --> 00:57:14.530
like with this beer--
that wild sourdough

00:57:14.530 --> 00:57:16.860
to help culture the beer.

00:57:16.860 --> 00:57:20.950
So it's a really
diverse beer state.

00:57:20.950 --> 00:57:24.720
I mean, it's a great
beer state, no doubt.

00:57:24.720 --> 00:57:28.670
Three beers that
you have to try.

00:57:28.670 --> 00:57:32.170
That's a really tough one.

00:57:32.170 --> 00:57:35.900
Because when you talk about--
is it the global beer scene.

00:57:35.900 --> 00:57:37.150
Is it the US beer scene?

00:57:37.150 --> 00:57:39.887
Is it your local beer scene?

00:57:39.887 --> 00:57:41.470
I think that there's
a couple of beers

00:57:41.470 --> 00:57:45.620
that have shaped
the US right now.

00:57:45.620 --> 00:57:48.770
Sierra Nevada Pale Ale, I
think everybody should taste.

00:57:48.770 --> 00:57:50.270
I think that's a great beer.

00:57:50.270 --> 00:57:54.820
That it has a great hop
characteristic to it.

00:57:54.820 --> 00:57:56.960
But it also has a great
malt characteristic to it.

00:57:56.960 --> 00:58:00.069
It's a very, very
well-balanced beer.

00:58:00.069 --> 00:58:01.360
It's a very easy drinking beer.

00:58:01.360 --> 00:58:02.901
And it's found
everywhere these days.

00:58:02.901 --> 00:58:06.450
And it can be easy to forget
that when it first came out,

00:58:06.450 --> 00:58:08.870
that it was revolutionary
in a lot of ways.

00:58:08.870 --> 00:58:13.240
So many-- if Ken Grossman was
inspired by Jack McAuliffe,

00:58:13.240 --> 00:58:15.450
whole new generations of
brewers were originally

00:58:15.450 --> 00:58:18.240
inspired by Sierra Nevada
and that particular beer.

00:58:18.240 --> 00:58:21.150
So that's a fun beer
to pay attention to.

00:58:24.210 --> 00:58:25.710
Man, I'm really
trying to think of--

00:58:25.710 --> 00:58:27.420
I already mentioned
Raspberry Tart

00:58:27.420 --> 00:58:30.107
from New Glarus, which is
for me, one of those ones

00:58:30.107 --> 00:58:31.190
that everybody should try.

00:58:31.190 --> 00:58:32.981
And they have an
interesting business model

00:58:32.981 --> 00:58:36.060
that they're doing more than
100,000 barrels of bee a year,

00:58:36.060 --> 00:58:38.480
and they're just staying
in the state of Wisconsin.

00:58:38.480 --> 00:58:42.497
They're choosing to stay
local, which is incredible

00:58:42.497 --> 00:58:44.330
when you think about
how people are shipping

00:58:44.330 --> 00:58:46.620
their beer around the
country and around the world.

00:58:50.040 --> 00:58:52.900
Will Myers makes that awesome
arquebus from Cambridge,

00:58:52.900 --> 00:58:54.730
but you can only
get it if you're

00:58:54.730 --> 00:58:58.390
at his pub in Cambridge,
Massachusetts.

00:58:58.390 --> 00:59:00.272
So that's a tough thing to say.

00:59:00.272 --> 00:59:01.980
AUDIENCE: We have an
office in Cambridge.

00:59:01.980 --> 00:59:03.896
JOHN HOLL: You do have
an office in Cambridge?

00:59:03.896 --> 00:59:04.870
Road trip.

00:59:04.870 --> 00:59:06.402
Let's go!

00:59:06.402 --> 00:59:08.610
Next summer we're all gonna
meet at Cambridge Brewing

00:59:08.610 --> 00:59:11.390
and we're all gonna
drink the arquebus.

00:59:11.390 --> 00:59:14.330
Yeah, I mean those kind
of jump out in my mind.

00:59:14.330 --> 00:59:17.320
But again, I've had
so many good beers.

00:59:17.320 --> 00:59:20.410
I've had these wonderful
bourbon barrel aged beers.

00:59:20.410 --> 00:59:23.910
Full Sail Brewing Company
does a bourbon barrel aged

00:59:23.910 --> 00:59:27.530
imperial stout every year that
has these really wonderful

00:59:27.530 --> 00:59:31.659
boozy, vanilla, woody notes to
them as well with the stout.

00:59:31.659 --> 00:59:34.200
And a lot of people are doing
bourbon barrel aged these days.

00:59:34.200 --> 00:59:36.710
If you love bourbon
and you love beer,

00:59:36.710 --> 00:59:38.880
it's just a perfect
marriage between the two,

00:59:38.880 --> 00:59:40.530
if it's done right.

00:59:40.530 --> 00:59:43.210
There's some really
wonderful Belgian Quads

00:59:43.210 --> 00:59:46.350
if you're really into
deep stone-fruity,

00:59:46.350 --> 00:59:50.150
boozy, foreign styles of beer.

00:59:50.150 --> 00:59:52.770
There's something beautiful
about just a normal Kolsch.

00:59:52.770 --> 00:59:57.900
A very simple German Kolsch
that is refreshing and light.

00:59:57.900 --> 01:00:03.180
And so, try them all.

01:00:03.180 --> 01:00:04.430
Follow your palate.

01:00:04.430 --> 01:00:05.970
I mean that's really it.

01:00:05.970 --> 01:00:08.230
Who am I to sit
up here-- I mean,

01:00:08.230 --> 01:00:13.530
except that I was invited
to-- to say, try these beers.

01:00:13.530 --> 01:00:14.357
Follow your palate.

01:00:14.357 --> 01:00:15.190
Follow your passion.

01:00:15.190 --> 01:00:17.720
Follow where your
taste buds move you.

01:00:17.720 --> 01:00:20.790
Because again, it's subjective.

01:00:20.790 --> 01:00:23.680
Whatever I say-- I could
say, oh this is a must

01:00:23.680 --> 01:00:24.560
try before you die.

01:00:24.560 --> 01:00:26.520
And you could drink it
and go, this is awful!

01:00:26.520 --> 01:00:28.561
He doesn't know what the
hell he's talking about!

01:00:28.561 --> 01:00:30.110
Personal palates are different.

01:00:30.110 --> 01:00:31.200
Do you have a question?

01:00:35.509 --> 01:00:37.800
AUDIENCE: So you were talking
about some of the reasons

01:00:37.800 --> 01:00:40.305
why people say they
don't like beer.

01:00:40.305 --> 01:00:40.930
JOHN HOLL: Yes.

01:00:40.930 --> 01:00:44.880
AUDIENCE: And one that
I hear in LA a lot

01:00:44.880 --> 01:00:48.540
is it's too many carbs.

01:00:48.540 --> 01:00:49.450
It's too heavy.

01:00:49.450 --> 01:00:51.150
Blah, blah, blah.

01:00:51.150 --> 01:00:57.470
Do you see anything in
the craft beer industry

01:00:57.470 --> 01:01:03.650
trying to tackle that, or
approach that, or market that?

01:01:03.650 --> 01:01:06.100
JOHN HOLL: So I'm
not in the best

01:01:06.100 --> 01:01:08.280
of physical conditions
as a beer drinker.

01:01:10.956 --> 01:01:13.270
So it's tough for me to talk
about the caloric intake.

01:01:13.270 --> 01:01:15.790
But here's the thing.

01:01:15.790 --> 01:01:19.300
A lot of people will cite
that beer is bad for you,

01:01:19.300 --> 01:01:21.920
or worse for you than wine or
spirits and that kind of thing.

01:01:21.920 --> 01:01:23.110
It's really not.

01:01:23.110 --> 01:01:26.150
It's comparable to some
of those, sometimes.

01:01:26.150 --> 01:01:29.480
But it's everything
in moderation.

01:01:29.480 --> 01:01:29.980
Really.

01:01:29.980 --> 01:01:34.449
If you're going to drink three
six packs a night, or three six

01:01:34.449 --> 01:01:34.990
packs a week.

01:01:34.990 --> 01:01:36.480
And then not work
out, and all that.

01:01:36.480 --> 01:01:36.979
Well yeah.

01:01:36.979 --> 01:01:38.320
It's going to be bad for you.

01:01:38.320 --> 01:01:40.900
But I've been out
traveling where

01:01:40.900 --> 01:01:43.680
I've seen people just kill
a bottle of wine themselves.

01:01:43.680 --> 01:01:46.100
And that's not better for you.

01:01:46.100 --> 01:01:47.950
It's not much [INAUDIBLE].

01:01:47.950 --> 01:01:49.620
What we've seen
though is there's

01:01:49.620 --> 01:01:51.400
a lot of the larger
beer companies that

01:01:51.400 --> 01:01:54.860
market to a lower
calorie intake.

01:01:54.860 --> 01:01:58.646
So ones that say, we
only have 65 calories.

01:01:58.646 --> 01:02:00.770
Or we only have 100 calories,
and things like that.

01:02:00.770 --> 01:02:01.269
65.

01:02:01.269 --> 01:02:03.120
No, I wasn't trying
to like-- I'm

01:02:03.120 --> 01:02:04.390
getting corrected in the back.

01:02:04.390 --> 01:02:06.330
It's Miller 64!

01:02:06.330 --> 01:02:08.570
I was trying to give
them a pass on this one.

01:02:08.570 --> 01:02:11.630
I was trying to give them
a pass of just throwing out

01:02:11.630 --> 01:02:16.780
an arbitrary number then
a watered-down beer.

01:02:16.780 --> 01:02:20.180
But a Guinness, for example.

01:02:20.180 --> 01:02:23.200
They had a big advertising
campaign a couple of years ago,

01:02:23.200 --> 01:02:26.550
it has about 125 calories in it.

01:02:26.550 --> 01:02:27.050
Right?

01:02:27.050 --> 01:02:29.240
People would think
that it has a lot more.

01:02:29.240 --> 01:02:32.290
Your normal beers are
somewhere in the 100 to 200

01:02:32.290 --> 01:02:34.160
calorie range.

01:02:34.160 --> 01:02:37.360
It's not that bad for you,
considering everything else

01:02:37.360 --> 01:02:39.280
that we might eat
during the day.

01:02:39.280 --> 01:02:41.572
It's just that perception
that beer makes you bloated,

01:02:41.572 --> 01:02:43.530
or beer makes you fat,
or you get a beer belly.

01:02:43.530 --> 01:02:46.160
Or all those manners
of things that wine

01:02:46.160 --> 01:02:47.730
has done a very good
job, and spirits

01:02:47.730 --> 01:02:50.190
have done a very good
job of sort of playing up

01:02:50.190 --> 01:02:52.030
the sophistication
and the health aspect,

01:02:52.030 --> 01:02:56.460
or the higher
aspect range of it.

01:02:56.460 --> 01:03:00.652
So it's not necessarily
bad for you.

01:03:00.652 --> 01:03:02.110
It's just everything
in moderation.

01:03:02.110 --> 01:03:02.776
AUDIENCE: Right.

01:03:02.776 --> 01:03:06.022
So my question was more
do you see something--

01:03:06.022 --> 01:03:08.467
because I agree with
you, I love beer.

01:03:08.467 --> 01:03:10.423
And I don't think
it's bad for you.

01:03:10.423 --> 01:03:12.868
But there's that
perception out there,

01:03:12.868 --> 01:03:16.780
whether you see something
in the marketing.

01:03:16.780 --> 01:03:20.203
Is that something that's
trying to be attacked head-on.

01:03:20.203 --> 01:03:23.002
Or if it's just conversations
like these where you say--

01:03:23.002 --> 01:03:25.210
JOHN HOLL: It's not being
attacked head-on in the way

01:03:25.210 --> 01:03:27.880
that I would like the
industry to attack it head-on.

01:03:27.880 --> 01:03:31.330
I think that if brewers
started putting caloric intakes

01:03:31.330 --> 01:03:33.740
on there, I think it
could help or hurt.

01:03:33.740 --> 01:03:36.950
Because you're going
to get some beers that

01:03:36.950 --> 01:03:39.090
are going to have
600 calories in them,

01:03:39.090 --> 01:03:40.880
just given by the
nature of the sugar.

01:03:40.880 --> 01:03:43.220
And they're not going to
want to put that on there.

01:03:43.220 --> 01:03:46.370
And if one brewery makes a
beer that has 100 calories,

01:03:46.370 --> 01:03:49.480
and the same brewery
makes one that has 600,

01:03:49.480 --> 01:03:50.960
do you do a blanket or not?

01:03:50.960 --> 01:03:53.930
And then you're going to get
accused of false advertising.

01:03:53.930 --> 01:03:56.790
So I think it's a slippery
slope for a lot of them.

01:03:56.790 --> 01:04:00.420
Every couple years that
"Eat This, Not That,"

01:04:00.420 --> 01:04:02.990
"Drink This, Not That."
book comes back into vogue.

01:04:02.990 --> 01:04:06.270
And invariably they show
up on the Today Show.

01:04:06.270 --> 01:04:08.710
And it's have this
beer that's like water.

01:04:08.710 --> 01:04:12.110
And not this barleywine
that has 600 calories.

01:04:12.110 --> 01:04:14.450
You can't even
compare the two beers.

01:04:14.450 --> 01:04:17.080
And it's like if I'm going
to drink this barleywine,

01:04:17.080 --> 01:04:18.900
that means I'm only
going to have one.

01:04:18.900 --> 01:04:21.530
And it means that
rather than drinking

01:04:21.530 --> 01:04:24.430
six of those, which would
actually equal one of these.

01:04:24.430 --> 01:04:27.020
And that's something
that we need to change.

01:04:27.020 --> 01:04:29.890
But that's a question for
the individual brewers.

01:04:29.890 --> 01:04:31.640
There's not an easy
answer, unfortunately,

01:04:31.640 --> 01:04:33.580
for that at this point.

01:04:33.580 --> 01:04:35.650
The other thing,
just perception-wise,

01:04:35.650 --> 01:04:38.390
we were talking about
calories, one of the things

01:04:38.390 --> 01:04:40.140
I wanted to point out
just really quickly.

01:04:40.140 --> 01:04:43.260
As you look at the bottles
up there that we had today,

01:04:43.260 --> 01:04:46.820
you'll see a lot of the famous
brown glass 12-ounce bottles.

01:04:46.820 --> 01:04:51.874
But you also see the larger
22-ounce bottle of the IPA.

01:04:51.874 --> 01:04:53.540
And then that really
cool-looking bottle

01:04:53.540 --> 01:04:57.010
that we have with this blonde
that we're drinking right now.

01:04:57.010 --> 01:04:59.010
And then there's also the can.

01:04:59.010 --> 01:05:00.660
Which I always
love pouring cans,

01:05:00.660 --> 01:05:03.140
because people think that
can is a lesser vessel.

01:05:03.140 --> 01:05:04.400
It's really not.

01:05:04.400 --> 01:05:05.570
It keeps out light.

01:05:05.570 --> 01:05:06.997
It's easier to ship.

01:05:06.997 --> 01:05:09.330
Keeping out light helps the
beer from getting that skunk

01:05:09.330 --> 01:05:12.630
flavor, that oxidation
flavor as well.

01:05:12.630 --> 01:05:14.460
It's lighter, so
it ships easier.

01:05:14.460 --> 01:05:16.500
It's stackable.

01:05:16.500 --> 01:05:17.590
You can take it camping.

01:05:17.590 --> 01:05:19.030
You can take it to the poolside.

01:05:19.030 --> 01:05:21.270
You can take it to the
shore without worrying

01:05:21.270 --> 01:05:22.520
about broken glass.

01:05:22.520 --> 01:05:25.510
So don't dismiss beers in cans.

01:05:25.510 --> 01:05:27.290
I hope you all like
that flavorful beer.

01:05:27.290 --> 01:05:30.830
You can crush it on your head
after you're done drinking it,

01:05:30.830 --> 01:05:31.880
if you're really into it.

01:05:31.880 --> 01:05:34.250
And if you've had a couple.

01:05:34.250 --> 01:05:35.890
So yeah, don't dismiss
a beer in a can,

01:05:35.890 --> 01:05:38.370
because I'm sure as
you were drinking it,

01:05:38.370 --> 01:05:39.870
you didn't notice
any off flavors.

01:05:39.870 --> 01:05:42.450
And you hopefully
enjoyed that beer.

01:05:42.450 --> 01:05:43.610
And that came from a can.

01:05:43.610 --> 01:05:48.180
So don't dismiss
it when you see it.

01:05:48.180 --> 01:05:49.900
So thanks so much, guys.

01:05:49.900 --> 01:05:52.600
This was really cool
for me to be here.

01:05:52.600 --> 01:05:56.840
It's a company that I've
long admired from afar.

01:05:56.840 --> 01:05:59.610
So to sit here with you guys and
be able to talk about the thing

01:05:59.610 --> 01:06:02.490
that I love and the place
where you guys work and love

01:06:02.490 --> 01:06:04.720
has been a really cool
experience for me.

01:06:04.720 --> 01:06:07.690
And I hope that you enjoy
the book and your beer

01:06:07.690 --> 01:06:08.770
and food-tasting journey.

01:06:08.770 --> 01:06:10.170
I hope to come back and
do a beer dinner with you

01:06:10.170 --> 01:06:11.000
guys at some point.

01:06:11.000 --> 01:06:11.500
Cheers.

01:06:11.500 --> 01:06:13.000
Thanks so much.

01:06:13.000 --> 01:06:14.550
[APPLAUSE]

